arily to house working-class people, and he was a cofounder of the Regional Planning Association of America. As a planner, designer, and, at times, financier of new housing developments, Stein wrestled with the challenges of creating what today we would term "livable," "walkable," and "green" communities during the ascendency of the automobile. He managed these challenges by partnering private capital with government funding, as well as by collaborating with colleagues in planning, architecture, real estate, and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitectsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aArchitectszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aCity plannersxBiographyxUnited States. 0aCity plannerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aGarden citiesxHistoryxUnited StatesxUnited StatesxBiographyxHistory. 0aGarden citieszUnited StatesxHistoryvBiography. 4aArchitecture & Preservation. 4aArt History. 4aBiography & Autobiography.  aRegional Planning Association of America, housing planning, policymaking, housing development, urban development, investment housing, community design, sustainable housing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2016z9783110482812oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170614140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501706141423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501706141/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DADb2016  aZDB-23-DGG